The sixth development pushed in a related direction but focused on rights and protections. The Education Department\'92s Civil Rights Division abolished more than half of its offices through layoffs, sharply limiting federal capacity to investigate discrimination in schools. The broader Education workforce was halved, and federal diversity programs across government were terminated by executive order. These institutional changes were mirrored in policy: Trump ordered transgender women in federal custody transferred to men\'92s prisons despite prior court rulings, and the Wyoming legislature passed multiple bills restricting transgender rights in sports and public facilities.\
\
Labor and social protections weakened alongside civil\uc0\u8209 rights enforcement. TSA employees lost collective bargaining rights, making it easier for management to discipline or reassign frontline security staff. The Social Security Administration\'92s new overpayment rules allowed full benefit clawbacks, and cuts to school and food\u8209 bank programs reduced access to nutrition for children and low\u8209 income families. Medical research and teacher\u8209 training funds faced deep reductions, including canceled grants to Johns Hopkins and planned cuts to teacher preparation that were only temporarily blocked by court order.\
\
These moves did not ban equality or unionism outright. They removed the scaffolding that had made rights enforceable and protections real. With fewer investigators, fewer offices, and fewer legal hooks, individuals facing discrimination or arbitrary treatment had less institutional backing. The state\'92s posture shifted from active guardian of civil rights and labor standards to a more indifferent, and sometimes hostile, manager.\
